value.value: Skeletogenic cell that is terminally differentiated, secretes an avascular, GAG-rich matrix, is embedded in cartilage tissue matrix, retains the ability to divide, and develops from a chondroblast cell.
Skeletogenic cell that secretes dentine matrix, is derived from odontogenic papilla. Embedded in dentine tissue, and is the transformation of a non-terminally differentiated odontoblast cell.
An osteocytelike cell with numerous processes, trapped in a lacuna in the cement of the tooth.

definition.value: CHECK: wikipedia says that cementocytes no longer produce cementum, but the phenoscape def is: Skeletogenic cell that produces cementum, is part of the odontogenic papilla, and is a transformation of a cementoblast cell (no change to existing def).

value.value: A cell occurring in the peripheral part of the vitreous body of the eye that may be responsible for production of hyaluronic acid and collagen.
A cell capable of processing and presenting lipid and protein antigens to T cells in order to initiate an immune response.

definition.value: Note change of name; nearly all somatic cells can present antigens to T cells via MHC Class I complexes leading to effector responses, but professional antigen presenting cells constitutively express MHC Class II as well as costimulatory molecules, and thus can initiate immune responses via T cells.

value.value: A pigment cell is a cell that contains pigment granules.
A pigment cell derived from the neural crest. Contains melanin-filled pigment granules, which gives a brown to black appearance.
A specialized epithelial cell that is capable of synthesizing and secreting certain biomolecules.
A cell that specializes in controlled release of one or more substances.
A cell of an exocrine gland; i.e. a gland that discharges its secretion via a duct.
A cell that secretes glycosaminoglycans.
A cell that is usually basal in position, cuboidal with round nucleus, short microvilli, secretes pepsinogen.
A cell that specializes in secretion of surfactant in the alveoli of the lung.

Epithelial progenitor cell of the lung. Club cells are dome-shaped with short microvilli but no cilia. They function to protect the bronchiolar epithelium. Club cells also multiply and differentiate into ciliated cells to regenerate the bronchiolar epithelium.
A cell of the epithelial lining that produce and secrete mucins.
A large, oval stomach epithelial cell with a central nucleus; source of gastric acid. Secretes HCl.
A cell of an endocrine gland, ductless glands that secrete substances which are released directly into the circulation and which influence metabolism and other body functions.
An endocrine cell that is located in the epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract or in the pancreas.
A neuron that is capable of some hormone secretion in response to neuronal signals.

The neurosecretory cell is neither an ordinary neuron nor an endocrine cell, but a combination of both. Its neuronal features resemble those of ordinary neurons concerning both structure and function. The production of a visible secretory material marks the neurosecretory neuron as a gland cell, and the fact that extractable cellular products act in the manner of hormones places it in the realm of endocrine elements. 

The modern definition of neurosecretion has evolved to include the release of any neuronal secretory product from a neuron.

A cell that stores epinephrine secretory vesicles. During times of stress, the nervous system signals the vesicles to secrete their hormonal content. Their name derives from their ability to stain a brownish color with chromic salts. Characteristically, they are located in the adrenal medulla and paraganglia of the sympathetic nervous system.

label.value: Type B cell of pancreatic islet

value.value: A cell that secretes insulin and is located towards the center of the islets of Langerhans.

definition.value: Pancreatic beta cells are also reportedly CD284-positive. Upon activation, they upregulate their CD14 expression.

value.value: A cell that secretes glucagon.

label.value: Type A cell of pancreatic islet

value.value: A type of enteocrine cell found in the periphery of the islets of Langerhans that secretes glucagon.

label.value: Type D cell of pancreatic islet

value.value: A D cell located in the pancreas. Peripherally placed within the islets like type A cells; contains somatostatin.
A progesterone secreting cell in the corpus luteum. The large luteal cells develop from the granulosa cells. The small luteal cells develop from the theca cells.
A Leydig cell is a testosterone-secreting cell in the interstitial area, between the seminiferous tubules, in the testis.

definition.value: Note that the Amphibian Anatomy Ontology (AA) has a class 'leydig cells' but this is unrelated

value.value: A steroid hormone secreting cell that secretes estradiol.

The main structural component of the liver. They are specialized epithelial cells that are organized into interconnected plates called lobules. Majority of cell population of liver, polygonal in shape, arranged in plates or trabeculae between sinusoids; may have single nucleus or binucleated.

definition.value: Hepatocytes are reportedly MHC Class I-positive and MHC Class II-positive.

value.value: A cell whose primary function is to shorten.
Contractile cells resembling smooth muscle cells that are present in glands, notably the mammary gland, and aid in secretion. This cell has long weaving dendritic processes containing myofilament.
An animal cell that has characteristics of both a fibroblast cell and a smooth muscle cell.

definition.value: Myofibroblasts are alpha-SMA-positive, CD34-negative, CD45-negative. They are reportedly capable of secreting IL-1beta, IL-6, and TNF-alpha.

value.value: A mature contractile cell, commonly known as a myocyte. This cell has as part of its cytoplasm myofibrils organized in various patterns.
A somatic cell located in skeletal muscle.
A muscle cell that develops tension more slowly than a fast-twitch fiber.
A muscle cell that can develop high tension rapidly. It is usually innervated by a single alpha neuron.
A non-striated, elongated, spindle-shaped cell found lining the digestive tract, uterus, and blood vessels. They develop from specialized myoblasts (smooth muscle myoblast).
A striated muscle cell of an arthropod heart that participates in heart contraction.
